05033nam a22005895i 9780520961074DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20152015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209610747 a10.1525/97805209610742doi  a(DE-B1597)520314  a(OCoLC)947222590  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aN6537.F464b.G573 2015eb 7aART0150202bisacsh1 aGirardot, Norman J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEnvisioning Howard Finster :bThe Religion and Art of a Stranger from Another World /cNorman J. Girardot. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Internet Citations and Additional Web Resources -- tPreface: Stories about Stories -- tIntroduction. Once upon a Time: Encountering the Word Made Flesh -- tChapter 1. On the Finster Trail: The Business of Howard Finster's Divine Busyness -- tChapter 2. Signs of the Times: Howard Finster and Prophetic Reenchantment -- tChapter 3. The Matter of My Mission: Howard Finster's Religious Template -- tChapter 4. The First and Second Noah: Howard Finster's Ark of Myth and Meaning -- tChapter 5. The Finster Mythos: Just the Facts in Howard Finster's Mythic Life -- tChapter 6. Snakes in the Garden: Life and Death in Paradise -- tChapter 7. The Strange Beauty of Bad and Nasty Art: Toward a Finsterian Aesthetic -- tConclusion. Howard Finster: The Hidden Man of the Heart -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustrations -- tCredits and Permissions0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Reverend Howard Finster (1916-2001) was called the "backwoods William Blake" and the "Andy Warhol of the South," and he is considered the godfather of contemporary American folk and visionary art. This book is the first interpretive analysis of the intertwined artistic and religious significance of Finster's work within the context of the American "outsider art" tradition. Finster began preaching as a teenager in the South in the 1930s. But it was not until he received a revelation from God at the age of sixty that he began to make sacred art. A modern-day Noah who saw his art as a religious crusade to save the world before it was too late, Finster worked around the clock, often subsisting on a diet of peanut butter and instant coffee. He spent the last years of his life feverishly creating his environmental artwork called Paradise Garden and what would ultimately number almost fifty thousand works of "bad and nasty art." This was visionary work that obsessively combined images and text and featured apocalyptic biblical imagery, flying saucers from outer space, and popular cultural icons such as Elvis Presley, Marilyn Monroe, Henry Ford, Mona Lisa, and George Washington. In the 1980s and 90s, he developed cult celebrity status, and he appeared in the Venice Biennale and on the Tonight Show. His work graced the album covers of bands such as R.E.M. and Talking Heads. This book explores the life and religious-artistic significance of Finster and his work from the personal perspective of religion scholar Norman Girardot, friend to Finster and his family during the later years of the artist's life.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aArt and religionxUnited States. 0aArt and religionzUnited States. 0aFolk artistsxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aFolk artistszUnited States. 0aOutsider artxUnited States. 0aOutsider artzUnited States. 7aART / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978